{"cursor":"21147","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox military conflict |image= |caption= |conflict=Muslims conquest of\nNorth Africa |partof=the Muslim conquests and the ArabâByzantine Wars\n|date=647–709 |place=North Africa |result=Muslim victory |territory=North\nAfrica annexed by Muslims |combatant1=Byzantine Empire Berbers\n|combatant2=Rashidun Caliphate Umayyad Caliphate |commander1=Gregory the\nPatrician Dihya Kusaila John the Patrician |commander2=Abdallah ibn\nSa'ad Musa bin Nusayr Hasan ibn al-Nu'man |strength1= |strength2=\n|casualties1= |casualties2= }}\n\nThe 'Muslim conquest of North Africa' continued the century of rapid Arab Muslim\nmilitary expansion following the death of Muhammad in 632 AD. By 640 the Arabs\ncontrolled Mesopotamia, had invaded Armenia, and were concluding their conquest\nof Byzantine Syria. Damascus was the seat of the Umayyad caliphate. And by the\nend of 641 all of Egypt was in Arab hands. Then, with the destruction of the\nPersian army at the Battle of NihawÄnd (Nehawand) in 642, the conquest of the\nPersian Empire was essentially finished.\n\nIt was at this point that Arab military expeditions into North Africa were first\nlaunched by local initiative from Egypt, continuing for years and resulting in\nthe spread of Islam.\n\nIn 644 at Madinah, Caliph Umar (Omar) was succeeded by Uthman ibn Affan\n(Othman), during whose twelve-year rule Armenia, Cyprus, and all of Iran, would\nbe added to the growing Islamic empire; Afghanistan and North Africa would\nreceive major invasions; and Muslim sea raids would range from Rhodes to the\nsouthern coasts of the Iberian Peninsula. The Byzantine navy would be defeated\nin the eastern Mediterranean.\n","linknr":346,"url":"Muslim_conquest_of_the_Maghreb","recorded":1375074896,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Muslim_conquest_of_the_Maghreb&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Muslim_conquest_of_the_Maghreb&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opense